definition.value: VAM beta-lactamases are class B1 beta-lactamases found in Vibrio alginolyticus.

label.value: Miscellaneous ABC-F subfamily ATP-binding cassette ribosomal protection proteins

definition.value: ABC-F subfamily ATP-binding cassette ribosomal protection proteins of unknown, unclear or miscellaneous classification which nevertheless confer resistance to antibiotics through ribosomal protection and not through antibiotic efflux. These proteins should be further reviewed to elucidate associated genes, their function, origin and classification.

value.value: A thiol transferase isolated in Staphylococcus aureus that leads to resistance of fosfomycin.

An MCR-1-type colistin resistance gene variant, first described in a multi-drug-resistant Escherichia coli isolate recovered from a urinary tract infection, and co-occurring with the carbapenemase NDM-5.
An antibiotic-adjuvant admixture of the beta-lactam antibiotic ceftazidime and the non-beta-lactam beta-lactamase inhibitor avibactam.

label.value: Bacillus subtilis rpoB mutants conferring resistance to rifampin

value.value: Point mutations that occur within the Bacillus subtilis rpoB gene resulting in resistance to rifampin.
Capreomycin family of phosphotransferases confer resistance to capreomycin antibiotics.
cph is a phosphotransferase that confers resistance to capreomycin.
A fungal secondary metabolite which inhibits the action of New Delhi metallo-beta-lactamase 1.

definition.value: Molecules and compounds that decrease resistance by inhibiting the action of the MrsA efflux pump.

value.value: Luteolin is a flavonoid produced by a variety of plants that features a wide range of biological effects. It has been shown to inhibit the action of the MsrA drug efflux pump.
Pellitorine is a metabolite produced mainly in members of the Zanthoxylum, Tetradium, and Piper genera. It has been shown to inhibit the action of the MsrA drug efflux pump.
Piperic acid is a compound produced by members of the Piper genus. It has been shown to inhibit the action of the MsrA drug efflux pump.
Tetraydropiperine is a derivative of piperine produced by members of the Piper genus. It has been shown to inhibit the action of the MsrA drug efflux pump.
Sesamin is a compound isolated from sesame oil and bark from plants in the Zanthoxylum genus. It has been shown to inhibit the action of the MsrA drug efflux pump.
Biapenem is a broad spectrum injectable antibiotic belonging to the carbapenem subgroup of beta-lactams.
PRC beta-lactamases are class C beta-lactamases.
PRC-1 is a beta-lactamase that confers resistance to certain cephalosporins and penicillins.
Epinecidin-1 is a peptide antibiotic derived from Epinephelus coioides with broad spectrum activity against a range or Gram positive and Gram negative bacteria.
KPC-90 is a KPC beta-lactamase.

A peptidomimetic antibiotic with specific, potent action against members of the Pseudomonas genus. Murepavadin disrupts lipopolysaccharide biosynthesis by binding to lypopolysaccharide transport protein D.

Albendazole is a compound used in the treatment of parasitic worm infestations. It has been shown to exhibit antibiotic activity against Escherichia coli by inhibiting MurA (MurZ), thereby disrupting cell wall synthesis.

Diflunisal is a salicylic acid derivative and aspirin analogue typically used as a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug. It has been shown to exhibit antibiotic activity against Escherichia coli by inhibiting MurA (MurZ), thereby disrupting cell wall synthesis.

Gepotidacin is a triazaacenaphthylene bacterial type II topoisomerase inhibitor used experimentally. It has been in phase III of clinical trials since 2019 for the treatment of gonorrhea, however gepotidacin has demonstrated antibiotic activity against a variety of bacteria.

Klebsidin is a peptide antibiotic derived from Klebsiella pneumoniae that exhibits activity against members of the Enterobacteriaceae family of Gram-negative bacteria, including Escherichia and Salmonella species. Klebsidin acts by accumulating in the target cell and inhibiting RNA polymerase.

Fisetin is a flavonoid produced mainly by plants in the Eudicotidae clade. It exhibits a range of biological activities such as anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties, and fisetin has been shown to inhibit the action of metallo-beta-lactamases.
Risedronate is a bisphosphonate used as an oral medication to treat osteoperosis and Paget's disease of bone. It has been shown to inhibit the action of New Delhi metallo-beta-lactamase-1.

Methotrexate is an antifolate chemotherapeutic and immune suppressant used to treat a wide variety of cancers and autoimmune diseases. It has been shown to inhibit the action of New Delhi metallo-beta-lactamase-1.
FosM1 is a thiol transferase discovered in human gut microflora that leads to the resistance of fosfomycin.
FosM2 is a thiol transferase discovered in human gut microflora that leads to the resistance of fosfomycin.
FosM3 is a thiol transferase discovered in human gut microflora that leads to the resistance of fosfomycin.

label.value: class A Bacillus cereus Bc beta-lactamase

value.value: Class A Bacillus cereus Bc beta-lactamases are enzymes that break down beta-lactam antibiotics, particularly penicillins.
Bacillus cereus beta-lactamase III is a class A beta-lactamase that breaks down a number of penicillins and cephalosporins in Bacillus cereus.

Nitroimidazole reductases are a group of enzymes that deactivate nitroimidazole antibiotics by reducing their nitro functional group to an amino group. These enzymes are associated with resistance to nitroimidazole derivatives in Bacteroides fragilis but have also been reported in a variety of anaerobic Gram-negative and Gram-positive genera. The minimum inhibitory concentrations for these enzymes vary greatly depending on species, strain, and precise nitroimidazole treatment used.

nimA is a nitroimidazole reductase mainly found in Bacteroides fragilis that is associated with the deactivation of nitroimidazole antibiotics such as metronidazole. Minimum inhibitory concentrations observed in isolates vary greatly depending on species, strain, and nitroimidazole treatment.

nimC is a nitroimidazole reductase mainly found in Bacteroides fragilis that is associated with the deactivation of nitroimidazole antibiotics such as metronidazole. Minimum inhibitory concentrations observed in isolates vary greatly depending on species, strain, and nitroimidazole treatment.

nimE is a nitroimidazole reductase mainly found in Bacteroides fragilis that is associated with the deactivation of nitroimidazole antibiotics such as metronidazole. Minimum inhibitory concentrations observed in isolates vary greatly depending on species, strain, and nitroimidazole treatment.
nimF is a nitroimidazole reductase that shares significant identity with other nim genes which are associated with the deactivation of nitroimidazole antibiotics.
nimG is a nitroimidazole reductase that shares significant identity with other nim genes which are associated with the deactivation of nitroimidazole antibiotics.

nimH is a nitroimidazole reductase mainly found in Bacteroides fragilis that is associated with the deactivation of nitroimidazole antibiotics such as metronidazole. Minimum inhibitory concentrations observed in isolates vary greatly depending on species, strain, and nitroimidazole treatment.

nimI is a nitroimidazole reductase discovered in the Prevotella baroniae that is associated with the deactivation of nitroimidazole antibiotics such as metronidazole. Although not found in Bacteroids fragilis, the source organism of most nim genes, nimI shares significant similarity with other nitroimidazole reductases. nimI is chromosomally encoded in P. baroniae, suggesting that it is intrinsic to this species.

nimJ is a nitroimidazole reductase mainly found in Bacteroides fragilis that is associated with the deactivation of nitroimidazole antibiotics such as metronidazole. Minimum inhibitory concentrations observed in isolates vary greatly depending on species, strain, and nitroimidazole treatment.

nimK is a nitroimidazole reductase mainly found in Bacteroides fragilis that is associated with the deactivation of nitroimidazole antibiotics such as metronidazole. Minimum inhibitory concentrations observed in isolates vary greatly depending on species, strain, and nitroimidazole treatment.
Ornidazole is a synthetic nitroimidazole derivative mainly used to treat parasitic infections but has also demonstrated antibiotic activity against anaerobic bacteria.
Antibiotic-induced changes to cell morphology, including shape, volume and surface area, which decrease antibiotic susceptibility.
